# Theme Studio Operations

Operations are fine-grained units that perform a **single atomic action**: one logical unit of work. They live in `src/domain/operations/` and are composed by controllers. For layer placement and controller usage, see the Architecture rule (`.cursor/rules/vayeate-theme-studio-architecture.mdc`).

## Atomicity and scope

- **Single atomic action**: Each operation does one logical thing. Name and implement it so that it cannot be meaningfully split into smaller operations that would be invoked separately.
- **Single entity or batch**: An operation may act on a single entity (e.g. save one catalog) or on a batch of entities when the change is inherently one logical action (e.g. update a set of tokens that are always applied together). Use a batch only when the updates are inseparable in the domain.
- **No operation calls another operation**: Operations are fine-grained and single-responsibility. An operation must not invoke another operation; only controllers compose multiple operations (e.g. the load application controller invokes `clearPersistedUndo` and any other operations needed for bootstrap).

## Coupling

- **Inherent coupling**: All changes performed by an operation must be executed together. Partial execution (doing one part without the others) is not allowed. If two updates can be done independently, they belong in separate operations.
- **Controllers**: Controllers compose one or more operations. They must not split a single logical action across multiple operations in a way that would allow partial application. When a user action requires several steps, the controller may call several operations in sequence, but each operation remains one atomic, coupled unit.

## Adding or modifying operations

When adding, updating, or modifying operations, use the add-or-modify-operation skill (`.cursor/skills/add-or-modify-operation/SKILL.md`) and follow the conventions in the Architecture and Action Queue rules.
